'''Level 312''' is the 313th level of the backrooms. Known for it's extreme, sunny heat and phase progression.<div style="font-family:Amatic SC; background: #C96615; color: #5E3509; border:3px solid #000000; box-shadow: 0px 0px 7px #000000; padding:5px 10px; margin:1em; text-align:center;"><font size="5">Description</font></div>

== Introduction: ==
Level 312, nicknamed '''''“The Sunny Station,”''''' manifests as an abandoned metropolitan train terminal perpetually stuck in an afternoon setting. The level is illuminated by the golden afternoon light. The level's atmosphere is a little strange, considering that the light coming into this level is tinged with this brownish-orange tint, which gives it a strange and liminal vibe. The air itself is also orange and is seemingly contaminated with some unknown gas. It is currently unknown if the gas is harmful or not, but it's best to avoid breathing it in too much and to stay in areas where there's less of it. Currently, [[The Kauer Research Organization]] is researching the gas, so we don't know anything about it yet. The level is initially safe, but it gets increasingly hostile to the point of terminal environmental collapse, as indicated by its class description. As per advice, it has been said, "The level is deceptively safe, but the longer you stay there, the more dangerous the level gets, so make sure to escape this level as soon as possible and to not mistakenly enter this level at any cost."

=== Upon Arrival: ===
Upon arrival, wanderers will usually experience a profound sense of calm and familiarity, as if they’ve been here before— which being the main reason for the level's danger. Dust motes drift lazily through the sunlight. The air of this level smells faintly of metal and warm rain. Although, the first thing wanderers hear upon arrival is a fiery, almost Arabic-themed instrumental song playing in the level, the one you're hearing right now while reading this article. The song seems to be playing from the randomly dotted-around speakers found in the hallways area. It is unknown as to why the song exists, who created it, and why it's playing on this level. The speakers are only placed in very key and rare spots within the hallways part of this level, and the music also plays from the vinyl in the entrance room. So it's somewhat but not too rare to come across music on this level. There are two major areas currently known at this level. They will be explained later on.{{Blurimage|file=SunnyStation.jpg|hovertext=The Sunny Station.|caption=One of the hallways on the level.|align=3}}

=== Isolating Properties: ===
No two wanderers or groups of wanderers that came from different sources can be on this level at the same time. If any wanderer finds themselves alone and doesn't have anyone beside them and gets sent to this level, then no matter how much one searches inside the level, one wouldn't find another person. Only one person can be in the level at the same time. It seems like the [[Phenomenon 15|Phenomenon]] is present in this level as well. Although, there is a special case where one person, if they have another person directly touching them while they're going to this level, they may be able to get to this level with that said person. Which is thought to be a glitch in the [[Phenomenon 15|phenomenon.]]

=== The Main Hall: ===
The Main Hall is the first of the two major areas of this level. It is usually one of the first areas that wanderers will go through in this level. The main hall is located right in the center of the level. It is thought to be the place this level originated from, the first place that formed during level 312's creation. To enter the main hall, well, you have a 50% chance of spawning in here when getting to this level. If you don't spawn in here, you may get sent to a minor, much smaller area called "The entrance." More on that later—but for now, remember that you just have to walk through that door in the entrance room to get to the main hall. To exit the main hall, you can open a large glass door further down, which will lead you to the hallways. So far, the main hall is the biggest part of the level, spanning nearly the entirety of the level and it's also the place you'll spend the most time in. It's literally what this level is named after.

==== Visual description of The Main Hall: ====
The main hall resembles a classic metropolitan train terminal. It is enormous—endless marble floors, glass ceilings, and motionless trains resting on silent tracks. The signs in the terminal flicker overhead, displaying meaningless destinations like ''“Platform 0 – All Departures”'' or ''“Next Train: Never.”'' To this day, nobody has yet figured out why the signs display this or the meaning of all this. For the first few hours, the environment is stable. The temperature is comfortable, light consistent, and no entities are visible. However, the longer one remains, the level begins to subtly ''change''.

=== The Hallways: ===
The hallways are another part of this level. It's currently the second known major part of level 312 besides the main metropolitan train station area. The hallways can be accessed by wandering around the main hall; then you'll eventually come across a unique-looking glass door. Entering it will leave you here. To exit, you can backtrack to where you came from and exit from there. Or, you could wander around and find another glass door, which will lead you to the main hall.

==== Visual Description of The Hallways: ====
As the name suggests, the hallways manifest as, well, hallways. The walls of the hallways are made of tiles. The hallways are illuminated by the tube lights in the ceiling. The lights produce a fluorescent hum buzz similar to that of [[level 0]]. The hum buzz is louder than usual [[The Frontrooms|frontrooms]] lights make. The floor is made out of smooth concrete. The brownish-orange lighting/tint is also present in this part of the level as well as all the other parts of the level. Things are going quite smoothly right now, isn't it? The level currently doesn't seem that dangerous for a class 5e right now, right? I wonder if it would stay like this or if the level may ''change''.

=== The Minor Areas: ===
So far, we've only talked about the two major areas. But minor areas also exist. The difference between major and minor areas is that major areas are generally more important and are usually multi-roomed and huge. While on the other hand, minor areas are really small and unimportant and usually contain only 1 room.

==== The Entrance: ====
The entrance is usually one of the first minor areas that wanderers may get to. There is only 1 entrance room in the entire level and even then, your [[Phenomenon 15|version]] of the level may not even have it. The entrance acts as an introduction/tutorial for the level. It has many items, many visual indicators, and other things that prepare one for what's to ''come.'' To enter the entrance room, there is a 50% chance of just being sent in here as the first room. But if you don't get sent here, you will get sent to the main hall, and if that happens, you unfortunately won't be able to access the entrance. To exit it, you can open that door mentioned earlier and walk through it. Only a 50% chance of even experiencing this room.

===== Visual description of The Entrance: =====
The entrance resembles a vintage bar of sorts. It has a vinyl playing the level 312 music mentioned above. The entrance has a lot of resources, unlike the rest of the level. The resources are also not contaminated here, unlike everywhere else on the level. There are lots of almond water, energy bars, juice, and other useful resources to prepare you for the level. The walls in this bar have a nice, vintage wallpaper with a wooden partition beneath it. The floor is made out of polished hardwood and everything seems okay here.

==== The Storage Rooms: ====
The storage rooms are usually dotted throughout level 312. Unlike the entrance, there are multiple storage rooms dotted throughout the level and you have a 99.999999% chance of having them in your version of the level. If you don't, then it's a glitch in the [[Phenomenon 15|phenomenon]]. You can access the storage rooms by opening a metal door in the main hall or, one of the hallways on this level could lead to the storage room.

===== Visual description of the Storage Rooms: =====
The storage rooms, as their name suggests, resemble a storage room. Its architecture is very warehouse-like. Its layout is similar to that of [[level 3]]. The walls are made of white marble bricks. It is illuminated by tube lights. The lights here also produce a fluorescent hum buzz. But it's not as strong as the hum buzz of [[level 0]]. It's more like the hum buzz of a light in the [[The Frontrooms|frontrooms]]. There are often storage racks, loot boxes, machinery and industrial warehouse equipment. The racks often contain loot and resources, but beware! Those resources have a 20% chance of being contaminated. The loot boxes are like that of [[level 1]]. They can contain things ranging from gross stuff to useful stuff.

== Phase Progression: ==
You wander around the train terminal; everything's comfy—the temperature is a little warm, around 30-35 degrees, but it's nothing crazy when comparing it to what's to come. The trains are not moving yet; the tracks are silent, which is how they're supposed to be. But then, you feel a sensation creeping up your nerves. The environment of the level is slowly changing, and not for the better. It starts to get uncomfortable. Shadows start to appear at the corner of your vision. Something's changing for sure, and this is what we call, ''Phase Progression''.

=== What is Phase Progression? ===
A unique property of this level is the phase progression system. Basically, the level is split into multiple phases, each phase getting more dangerous than the last. Phase progression is a core part of this level. Without it, the level wouldn't be as anomalous. The phases change based on how much time you're spending on the level and what you're doing on the level.

=== Phase 1 – Comfort (1–3 hours) ===
Everything feels serene. The sunlight is soft and comfortably warm. Wanderers often feel drowsy or nostalgic in this phase, describing the sensation as “being home.” The music is still playing; everything is relaxed. The level may have mental effects on wanderers as well, making them nostalgic, which is very common for backrooms levels to do.

=== Phase 2 – Distortion (2–6 hours) ===
Phase 2, "Distortion," is the second phase. This is the phase when things start going crazy, so be prepared.

During the transition to this phase, the light gradually intensifies, taking on a deep blue hue—first amber, then red. Shadows begin stretching unnaturally, curving towards you. Your sanity starts to decrease. The terminal’s geometry starts looping; if you walk straight, then you may find yourself back where you began, yet slightly ''out of sync''. Time perception begins to falter. Both time and space start distorting.

Auditory hallucinations occur: announcements on the intercom, you may hear footsteps echoing behind, the sound of faint laughter. The sunlight no longer casts warmth—only heat.

To summarize, during phase 2, the light will gradually intensify. Shadows will start warping, sanity will decrease, and hallucinations occur. Time and space start to experience distortions.

=== Phase 3 – Overexposure (6–12 hours) ===
Phase 3 is the peak of human survival, the phase right before we reach terminal environmental collapse.

The environment becomes painfully bright. The temperatures may rise over 47 degrees Celsius. Surfaces emit a blinding, metallic glare. Many wanderers suffer from heatstroke in this phase. The extreme radiation exposure may cause skin cancer. Reflections in glass surfaces no longer match reality; instead, they show the wanderer staring back with a several-second delay.

The train’s doors begin to open and close on their own, releasing waves of dry, scorching air. The sound of machinery echoes beneath the station. Nobody knows why with concrete evidence. Maybe something vast moving in the tunnels. Prolonged exposure causes severe dehydration, skin burns, and memory loss. You may forget how they entered or why they stayed.

To summarize, during phase 3, the environment becomes very bright and the temperatures may rise over 47 degrees Celsius. Wanderers suffer from various diseases, including heatstroke. Radiation levels increase, and the train's doors behave abnormally.

=== Phase 4 – Collapse (12+ hours) ===
Phase 4 is the terminal collapse; there haven't been any reported cases of someone surviving this phase so far.

The sunlight fills everything and turns the level into an unending white expanse where outlines of architecture dissolve completely. Wanderers’ shadows completely vanish. They have vaporized due to the high levels of energy that are being released. The heat reaches lethal levels. Voices from the intercom now whisper, ''“All aboard.”''

Those who stay beyond this point are never properly seen again. The only visible thing is a faint outline, burned into the marble floor, maybe the remains of where they stood or some other anomalous sign.

To summarize, during phase 4, the sunlight fills up everything and turns the level completely white. The level dissolves, and the wanderers vaporize due to the high energy. The heat is lethal and the intercoms say, "All aboard."

== Entities ==
The level has '''no active entities''' during early phases. However, in the later stages, silhouettes appear within the glare. They are most probably hallucinations. They are tall, human-shaped forms standing motionless on the platforms. Although the [[M.E.G.]] doesn't agree, many conspiracy theorists believe these to be the '''residual echoes''' of those who overstayed. Although their movement is only visible in reflections, never directly.

== Bases, Outposts, and Communities ==
None.

Attempts to establish long-term outposts fail as the level destabilizes beyond several hours. Any equipment left behind disintegrates into ash-like residue of fine, glowing dust. Although groups from other levels do send out patrols to investigate this level well, patrols of 1 person specifically due to the [[Phenomenon 15|phenomenon]]. They usually have varying safety equipment and an alarm given to the researcher whenever it gets near 12:12 o'clock for them to exit safely. The groups that study this level are [[M.E.G.]], [[Backroom Colonists|The Backroom Colonists]], [[The Kauer Research Organization]], and many other groups.

== Resources ==
There aren't many resources in this level. They're somewhat rare in this level. It's rare to even find a bottle of [[Object 1|Almond Water]] here, let alone any other meaningful resources. As the research of the [[The Kauer Research Organization]] suggests, when you do find [[Object 1|Almond Water]], there's a 20% chance that it is contaminated with [[Object_33|Memory Flame]], so it's probably better to not drink any [[Object 1|Almond Water]] that you may find on this level. Other than that, you may also find randomly scattered around "water bottles" in this level. But don't be fooled, that is not water. It's actually a transparent form of [[Object 12|Liquid Pain]] that's disguised as water, inside bottles falsely branded to BE real water. This variation of [[Object 12|Liquid Pain]] only exists in this level. There is also a lot of junk and other anomalous resources like that, but they are usually completely useless and are just there for show. This level is one of the worst places to go if you want to hunt resources.

== Entrances and Exits ==

=== Entrances ===

* Taking a train in [[Level 11|'''Level 11''']] that displays a sign labeled "no destination" leads here.
* Rarely, opening a maintenance door in [[Level 1|'''Level 1''']] with sunlight visible behind it will transport the wanderer to Level 312.

=== Exits ===

* The only known exit appears during '''Phase 2''', when the clock above the main concourse reads '''12:12'''. Entering the nearest train at that exact moment will bring the wanderer to '''[[Level 10]].'''
* After '''Phase 3''', no exits have ever been confirmed. Most of phase 3 has been documented just through studying the broken audio logs. And phase 4 through highly heat-resistant drones developed by the [[M.E.G.]]

