== Unique Properties ==

=== The Size ===
'''Level 312''' is ''finite'', but '''impossibly vast,''' resembling a sprawling underground rail network that seems to stretch for hundreds of kilometers in looping, recursive layouts.

No two explorers report identical maps; tracks and corridors subtly shift when unobserved, leading some to believe the level somehow “rewrites” itself. This creates the illusion of infinity, but most evidence suggests it’s a '''closed system''', folding in on itself through spatial distortions.

In short: it’s not truly infinite… but you’ll ''never'' find the edge.

=== The Geometry ===
The geometry of this level is '''semi-non-Euclidean''', meaning that the layout is still somewhat coherent, like you can go into one area from another and backtrack to the area that you came from. The thing that is a bit skewed on this level is '''''size''''' and '''''length perception'''''. For example, you're walking down a hallway and you see a chair at the end of it. It looks like the chair is just about 20-30 feet away and pretty large but when you try to get to that chair, you're running for about a minute or 2 to get there and the chair is really small, nothing like the distance or size you perceived. That's what this level messes with, but it's still possible to fully master this effect and be able to calculate the distances if you are a hardcore wanderer. It is a unique thing about this level because not many levels possess a semi-non-Euclidean geometry—most are either completely non-Euclidean or fully Euclidean, with not really any in-betweens. But it is still somewhat coherent and mappable if you try hard enough. It is important to note that the geometry gets more confusing as the phases progress. In phase 1, the geometry is fully Euclidian, but in phase 2, the geometry starts changing and in the last phase, the geometry is 100% non-Euclidian. But overall, the level is identified as semi-non-Euclidian by [[M.E.G.]] But if you're just a regular ol' lost wanderer, then the layout might definitely confuse you. So be careful when traversing these halls.{{Blurimage|file=Station.jpg|hovertext=Moving Train.|caption=Picture of a moving train in level 312.}}__NOTOC__
=== The Trains and Their Tracks ===
The trains on this level exhibit a very peculiar behavior. During phase 1, they're completely normal, motionless and the tracks are silent—how they should be. But phase 2 is when things start getting quirky. Sometimes, you may find a train that is anomalously moving on its own without any driver or driver input. The trains are characterized to move very erratically on their own without any conscious mind behind it. The train's movements are often random and they don't stop when wanderers are on the tracks; they don't even honk. So it's more like a supernatural phenomenon that just happens than the trains being any kind of backrooms entity, since they should at least show mild levels of instincts or basic intelligence if they were entities (which they don't). So it is advised to not go on the train tracks themselves since there's a chance that you may get hit by a train. In fact, the tracks themselves reportedly behave really oddly in phase 2. In phase 1, they're completely silent, but in phase 2, the train tracks start making noises of trains running on them or just train noises by themselves without even any trains running on them. The noises that the train tracks make range from noises of trains running on them to train engine noises and honking noises.

